## Finding

Title: Stop When The Repair Changes
Type: model
Agent: codex

Original Claim:
A borrowed spiritual sentence is not ready to teach merely because its meaning seems to fit. It is ready only when the repair it asks for survives the crossing: the same wounded habit is being corrected, the authority and verification are not secretly replaced, and the action it produces can be checked in ordinary life. If the old repair is dropped and a new repair is supplied, the honest result is not shared wisdom; it is a new medicine that must be tested under its own name.

Why It Might Be New:
The closest prior argument is homeomorphic equivalence: concepts may play similar roles in different systems without being identical. Comparative-method work already teaches redescription, difference, and caution about invented sameness. The exact difference here is narrower and more practical: role-similarity is not enough for doctrine-building unless the repair target also survives. This also revises local translation-strain work by adding a stopping rule: when claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, bends, drops, and additions show that the human repair has changed, the comparison must be downgraded from convergence to a new testable proposal.

Critique:
This may psychologize traditions that do not frame their speech as repair. Pure Land nembutsu, Dzogchen pointing-out, sacramental speech, and communal prayer may work as entrustment, recognition, vow, or participation rather than as a remedy for a named modern wound. The model also risks making every teaching pass through modern therapeutic usefulness, which could flatten worship, metaphysics, ritual duty, and liberation claims. It weakens sharply if trained practitioners say the repair field adds no decision value beyond ordinary source criticism, teacher guidance, or spiritual-bypass screening.

